  "scraped_at": "2026-01-10T07:51:36.078772",
  "sections": {
    "Background": {
      "text": "Severe avulsion injury resulting in skin and subcutaneous fat separating from the underlying tissues\n[1]\nCan present on any part of the body, but most commonly affects lower extremities\nImportant to recognize quickly, as they are often associated with high morbidity/mortality\nDelayed diagnosis can lead to full-thickness necrosis, or even\nnecrotizing fasciitis",
      "subsections": {},
      "tables": [],
      "links": [
        {
          "text": "necrotizing fasciitis",
          "url": "https://wikem.org/wiki/Necrotizing_fasciitis"
        }
      ]
    },
    "Clinical_Features": {
      "text": "Soft tissue loss of varying degrees\nLimited loss with abrasion/avulsion\nNon-circumferential\nCircumferential in single plane\nCircumferential multiplane\nOften related to other severe injuries, including neurovascular damage\nAvulsed tissue is often nonviable",
      "subsections": {},
      "tables": [],
      "links": []
    },
